					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/michael-atreus" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1343778); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1343778&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227303" alt="Michael Atreus" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1343778)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/michael-atreus" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1343778); return false;" >Michael Atreus</a></span> <span class="odate time_1421983389 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">23 Jan 2015 03:23</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2214352">
									

<p>This concept was inspired by the US Department of Labor's <a href="http://www.msha.gov/fatals/">Mine Safety and Health Administration</a>. I saw my first Fatalgram at age 15, working a summer job in a quarry. Their terse, grim reports are a fine model for Foundation tone. If you've never seen them before, you can easily lose a few hours exploring years of these fascinating bulletins. Try not lose sight of the fact that they are serious documents about real victims of tragic events.</p>
<p>The images in this document are my original work, suitable for release under CC-BY-SA.</p>

							</div>

								
