					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=455145&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227303" alt="Petrograd" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=455145)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/petrograd" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(455145); return false;" >Petrograd</a></span> <span class="odate time_1422140317 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">24 Jan 2015 22:58</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2215781">
									

<p>I agree with the details scorpion provided, but there's also a larger point. These aren't meant to figure out exact causes and completely prevent problems that are probably completely unpredictable. Bad shit is just going around SCPs, but just chalking it up to chance isn't going to help anyone. This process says that each death is important and a failure, and you have to try to derive whatever lessons you possibly can.</p>
<p>That's why I really love #6-13. It's clear that the safety council is both completely out of their depth in extracting broadly applicable lessons and that they've been at it a long time, and that even their specific findings can't help the next iterations. But it's still their responsibility to try and derive meaning from every needless death, and by God they're going to try for it.</p>

							</div>

								
					
